unity to pursue a master's degree at Columbia University in New York, Poitras was at the centre of the North American contemporary art scene. Together, these dual influences shaped Poitras' unique style, one that combines representational strategies of postmodern art - collage, layering, overpainting, incorporation of found objects - with a deep commitment to the politics and issues common to indigenous peoples. Cultural Memories and Imagined Futures: The Art of Jane Ash Poitras situates Poitras's work in the national context of Canadian First Nations art during the late 1980s and early 1990s, the period when she began to receive wide recognition. It is the first book-length study to examine Poitras's career as a whole, recounting her development as an artist, participation in major exhibitions, and recognition as a significant Canadian and international artist. Along with detailed analyses of specific artworks, Pamela McCallum has also compiled the most extensive bibliography of writings on Poitras to date.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndian art -- Canada. 0aIndian artzCanada. 0aIndians in art. 0aPoitras, Jane Ash -- Criticism and interpretation. 0aPoitras, Jane Ash. 0aSpirituality in art. 7aART / Canadian.2bisacsh  aCanadian art.  aCanadian artists.  aCanadian painter.  aalberta art.  aalberta artists.  aalberta painter.  abooks about canadian artists.  abooks about indigenous artists.  acanadian contemporary art.  acanadian first nations art.  acollage.  afamous canadian artists.  aindigenous art.  aindigenous artists.  aindigenous painter.  anorth American contemporary art.  apostmodern art.  arepresentational art.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruytert